# Naming Conventions

## Database & ORM (Drizzle)

This project uses **camelCase in TypeScript** and **snake_case in the database**.

### Drizzle Schema Pattern

```typescript
// ✅ CORRECT: camelCase property, snake_case column
transactionalEmail: boolean("transactional_email").notNull().default(true),
firstName: text("first_name"),
createdAt: timestamp("created_at").notNull(),

// ❌ WRONG: Don't use snake_case for the property name
transactional_email: boolean("transactional_email"),
```

### Better Auth Adapter

When creating/updating records via Better Auth's adapter, **always use camelCase**:

```typescript
// ✅ CORRECT: camelCase field names
await adapter.create({
  model: "user",
  data: {
    transactionalEmail: true,
    marketingEmail: false,
    createdAt: new Date(),
  },
});

// ❌ WRONG: snake_case will cause SQL errors
await adapter.create({
  model: "user",
  data: {
    transactional_email: true,  // WRONG!
    marketing_email: false,     // WRONG!
  },
});
```

### Direct Database Queries

When writing raw SQL or using Drizzle's query builder, reference the schema properties (camelCase):

```typescript
// ✅ CORRECT: Use schema property names
await db.update(userTable).set({ firstName: "John" });
await db.select({ email: userTable.email, name: userTable.firstName });

// Drizzle automatically maps to snake_case columns in SQL
```

## Summary

| Context | Convention | Example |
|---------|------------|---------|
| TypeScript properties | camelCase | `user.firstName` |
| Drizzle schema properties | camelCase | `firstName: text(...)` |
| Database columns | snake_case | `first_name` |
| Better Auth adapter data | camelCase | `{ firstName: "John" }` |
| API response JSON | camelCase | `{ "firstName": "John" }` |
